Eighty per cent (2002) were judged as 18 or older, while in further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18 years old".
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is called into question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent in recent months.
"We see no big difference in statistics of recent months, the numbers are quite constant," he said to The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases in which the person has been judged to be over 18 years does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker has lied about his or her age.
