NHS (The National Health Service) is to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
Patients will be given access to a "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September after a fight in front of the High Court against funding for the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that pre-sex pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by about 86%, will now be delivered by the health service for an initial three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to finance the trial after the Supreme Court of Appeals confirmed last year that the NHS had the power to pay for the PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS English chief Simon Stevens as' important new intervention ', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called this a' decisive moment '.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool, and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, and more clinics will follow in October, before it will be introduced across England in April 2018.
Predisposition prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV preparations taken before sex in order to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in cases where there is a risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that just enough drugs are present in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been treated successfully.
In clinics, appropriate participants who agree with the study are identified, including men, women, transgenders, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a family doctor can also register for participation in their local sex clinic.
The program will be £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to deliver drugs this week after an international competitive procurement.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence as used, recorded and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity's greatest health challenges. '
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National AIDS Trust) said: "This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, aimed at needy and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, people with high HIV risk will have access to this NHS-funded attempt in England to develop a new instrument that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiations with a partner, which will improve many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement. '
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority must now be to ensure that the study is carried out quickly throughout the country and that no one who has a risk to HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP test medicine has been obtained, we are well on the way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV. "
Sharon Hodgson, shadow health minister, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and delays by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention, and how to end the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This trial brings us a step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important for this study to be carried out as soon as possible throughout the country in order to protect people who are infected with HIV and to help bring us a step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society '.
