GMB concerns about investment at the McVitie factory in Glasgow
A trade union wants to check managers of the sponge manufacturer McVitie for the long-term commitment to production at their factory in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said that the company had been silent about the future of rabble-frontier investment.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which, among other products, produces Hobbons and Rich Tea biscuits.
McVitie's owner Pladis said he has invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be "first experienced" if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's director, GMB Scotland McVitie's called for "concern that financing for the modernization of production lines would not be pushed forward".
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy, said: "The fact that we cannot gain clarity from the General Suite Manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here, and the workforce is strongly focused on the local community and the Glasgow metropolitan area, an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social disadvantage.
Therefore, in the context of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living costs and chronic production decline, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving production presence at McVitie. "
A spokeswoman from Pladis said: "The branch manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday, and the company will respond directly because we appreciate the continuous commitment of employees and trade union representatives.
Two months ago we had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross, where some issues were discussed openly.
We discussed with our employees that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our divisions and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our rabble-rouser location, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a production site and, if our operations at the site change, employees and their trade union representatives will be the first to know. '
